line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">But why would Cerutti give up a job he relished=
 to run a smallish
museum? Some pointed to the fact that, despite his surname, the 58-year-old=
 is a Frenchman living in London, and Cerutti may be eager to get back in t=
he mix on his home turf. There=E2=80=99s no reason a few years in Paris bui=
lding up the Pinault collection wouldn=E2=80=99t give him a shot, with the =
right political breaks, at becoming minister of culture himself. What forme=
r chief of staff doesn=E2=80=99t dream of having the job he knows he could =
do better than his boss?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Some former Christie=E2=80=99s emp=
loyees, however, turned their thoughts in the opposite direction: With Pina=
ult gone and Cerutti back in Paris, wouldn=E2=80=99t the family begin to pu=
t out quiet feelers to sell the auction house? The art world continues to s=
peculate=E2=80=94without much evidence=E2=80=94that Fran=C3=A7ois-Henri is =
eager to part with his father=E2=80=99s other passion project. Even if that=
 were so, however, a dispassionate review of the Art=C3=A9mis portfolio=E2=
=80=94Kering, CAA, Christie=E2=80=99s, a
large chunk of Puma, several vineyards, a chain of restaurants that make Br=
etagne crepes (Pinault is from Brittany), and the Stade Rennais football cl=
ub=E2=80=94might favor keeping Christie=E2=80=99s in this day and age, when=
 fashion and art ricochet off each other in unexpected ways.</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:=
0px;">The oldest parlor game in the auction business, after all, is the ram=
pant speculation about who might buy Christie=E2=80=99s if the senior Pinau=
lt
were persuaded to sell. And while it might be easier to sell Christie=E2=80=
=99s after the transition at Art=C3=A9mis from father to son, it isn=E2=80=
=99t clear if such a transaction would ever be <em>easy</em>.=C2=A0</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">Christie=E2=80=99s is locked into a highly competitive duopoly=
 that can cause wild swings in revenue from year to year. Even if it weren=
=E2=80=99t so competitive with Sotheby=E2=80=99s, the supply of art and the=
 business cycles still
make the company anything but predictable. The lack of steady=E2=80=94even =
steadily declining=E2=80=94revenue and returns likely makes a deal less app=
ealing to private equity.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Fifteen years ago, <strong>=
Sheikh Hamad al-Thani</strong>, the emir of Qatar, floated the idea of maki=
ng a <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt=
2UktxclJLZ0dVZHBwVXYxWWhOZ3p3RnMwMHdraz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY2=
9tL2NvbnRlbnQvMTRjZDdkNWUtZGY4Yi0xMWRmLWJlZDktMDAxNDRmZWFiZGMwP3V0bV9jYW1wY=
Wlnbj1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MSUyRjE3JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1f=
Y29udGVudD1XYWxsK1Bvd2VyKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4MSUyRjE3JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ=
1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMj=
Z1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6ImY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZ=
DEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjk5MTAxNX0/7025eb546b3bae7e4c40bb3efad7a829963ad06e3a92=
1bcb3190db238e49fc79" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">bi=
d</a> for the
company in the <em>Financial Times</em>. Pinault didn=E2=80=99t flinch, so =
the Qataris instead hired Christie=E2=80=99s C.E.O. <strong>Ed Dolman </str=
ong>to run their museum authority and glorify the state. Would the al-Thani=
s revisit the idea? There was talk that the al-Thanis turned down the chanc=
e to buy Sotheby=E2=80=99s from <strong>Patrick Drahi</strong>. (They weren=
=E2=80=99t willing to meet his price, which included a slight profit.) Agai=
n, this talk may just be conjecture and schadenfreude. Almost no one has th=
e
access to actually <em>know</em> this. But the rumors convey the curiosity =
and concern surrounding both the auction house and Cerutti=E2=80=99s transi=
tion.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Anyway, to play out the thought, just for fun: if=
 the al-Thanis were to buy Christie=E2=80=99s while ADQ holds a significant=
 stake in Sotheby=E2=80=99s, an interesting new dynamic could unfold in the=
 marketplace. What would the Saudis do? Buy Phillips?=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0=
px;">That said, there=E2=80=99s always a chance that some centibillionaire =
tech bro or art- hoovering finance sky lord could swoop in and make Fran=C3=
=A7ois-Henri very happy. The only other obvious buyer is the man who tried =
to buy Sotheby=E2=80=99s in the wake of the price-fixing scandal, in 2000, =
then pivoted to backing <strong>Simon de Pury</strong> in acquiring a then =
much-smaller (can you imagine it) Phillips auction house. Having
gotten burned in the auction business, and effectively abandoning his stake=
 in Phillips, it would be another two decades before he took a run at Gagos=
ian, only to wind up with a likely disappointing financial relationship rat=
her than an ownership stake. I=E2=80=99m talking, of course, about Bernard =
Arnault.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;">Personally, I don=E2=80=99t doubt the Arnaults would want =
to buy Christie=E2=80=99s. But if they expressed interest, would the Pinaul=
ts
ever sell to them? Welcome to the art world=E2=80=A6</p></div>
